'''Amelia Egerton''' also known as '''Lady Amelia Hume''' (b. 1751, d. 1809) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[horticulturalist]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Harwood |first1=Kate |editor1-last=Rowe |editor1-first=Anne |title=Hertfordshire Garden History: A Miscellany |date=2007 |publisher=University of Hertfordshire Press |location=Hertfordshire |isbn=9781905313389 |page=67 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lUUE0XTqrWoC&pg=PA67 |accessdate=31 July 2018 |chapter=Some Hertforshire Nabobs |quote=Sir Abraham Hume II (1749-1838)...with his wife Amelia and head gardner James Mean, set about cultivating exotics.  They cultivated many rare plants, including those from the East Indies and India, between 1785 and 1825 and numerous examples still survive today.}}</ref>  She was also daughter of [[John Egerton (bishop)|John Egerton, Bishop of Durham]], wife of [[Sir Abraham Hume, 2nd Baronet]], and mother of [[Amelia Long|Amelia Long, Lady Farnborough]].<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Hall |editor1-first=Samuel Carter |title=The Vernon Gallery of British art, Volume 4 |date=1854 |publisher=George Virtue |location=London |page=117 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E75ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT117 |accessdate=31 July 2018 |chapter=Sir Abraham Hume, Bart.}}</ref>

