{{Infobox Officeholder | honorific-prefix = | name = Gilbert Anselme Girouard | honorific-suffix = | image = GilbertGirouard23.jpg | constituency_MP = [[Kent (New Brunswick electoral district)|Kent]] | parliament = Canadian | predecessor = [[George McLeod (New Brunswick politician)|George McLeod]] | successor = [[Pierre-Amand Landry]] | term_start = 1878 | term_end = 1883 | birth_date = {{birth date|1846|10|26}} | birth_place = Bouctouche, New Brunswick, Canada | death_date = {{death date and age|1885|01|13|1846|10|26}} | death_place = | nationality = | spouse = | party = [[Liberal-Conservative Party|Liberal-Conservative]] | relations = | children = | residence = | alma_mater = | occupation = | profession = | religion = }} '''Gilbert Anselme Girouard''' (October 26, 1846 &ndash; January 13, 1885) was a general merchant and political figure in [[New Brunswick]], Canada. He represented [[Kent (New Brunswick electoral district)|Kent]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] from 1878 to 1883 as a [[Liberal-Conservative]] member.
He was born in Ste-Marie de Buctouche, New Brunswick, and educated at [[University of St. Joseph's College|St. Joseph's College]] in [[Memramcook, New Brunswick|Memramcook]]. He taught school briefly in Sainte-Marie-de-Kent before becoming a general merchant in [[Buctouche, New Brunswick|Buctouche]] in 1870. In 1872, he married Sophia Baker. Girouard resigned his seat in 1883 to accept the position of customs collector for [[Richibucto, New Brunswick|Richibucto]]. He died of [[tuberculosis]] in Buctouche at the age of 38.
