'''Victor Hugo Blanc''' (August 31, 1897 – December 16, 1968) was a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] lawyer and politician from [[Philadelphia]].

Blanc was born in Philadelphia in 1897, the son of Samuel and Pauline Blanc. His parents were [[Jewish-American|Jewish]] immigrants from [[Odessa]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]] (modern-day [[Ukraine]]). Blanc graduated from [[West Philadelphia High School]] before attending the [[University of Pennsylvania]], where he received a [[bachelor's degree]] and a [[juris doctor|law degree]] in 1919 and 1923, respectively.{{sfn|Inquirer 1955}}  While still in college, he served in the [[United States Navy]] in [[World War I]].{{sfn|Inquirer 1968}}

Blanc had a private law practice before joining the [[Pennsylvania Attorney General|state Attorney General's]] office. He was active in Philadelphia civic organizations and served as president of the National League of [[Freemasonry|Masonic]] Clubs in 1938. At the outbreak of [[World War II]], Blanc rejoined the military, this time as an officer in the [[United States Army Air Corps]]. After the war, he continued his law practice, moving to work as an assistant district attorney in the [[District Attorney of Philadelphia|Philadelphia District Attorney]]'s office in 1950. As an assistant district attorney, Blanc won headlines by investigating police [[Graft (politics)|graft]]. That same year, he was named chairman of the County Board of Public Assistance.{{sfn|Inquirer 1955}}

[[Philadelphia municipal election, 1951|In 1951]], Blanc ran for [[Philadelphia City Council]]. Under the city charter adopted earlier that year, Philadelphians elected a seventeen-member city council, with ten members representing districts of the city, and the remaining seven being elected at-large; Blanc ran for one of the at-large seats. He won, part of a Democratic wave that swept the city government out of [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] control for the first time in 67 years.{{sfn|Inquirer 1951}} While on city council, Blanc led an investigation into corruption related to construction at [[Philadelphia International Airport]].{{sfn|Inquirer 1955}}

Blanc returned to prosecution [[Philadelphia municipal election, 1955|in 1955]] when he won election as District Attorney of Philadelphia, succeeding [[Richardson Dilworth]], who had resigned to run for mayor. Blanc, who won the Democratic primary unopposed, handily defeated Republican Wilhelm Knauer in the general election that November.{{sfn|Inquirer 1955}} Two years later, [[Philadelphia municipal election, 1957|in 1957]], he was elected to a four-year term, even though Mayor Dilworth, a fellow Democrat, declined to endorse him.{{sfn|Daily Times 1957}} Before that term ended, Governor [[David L. Lawrence]] appointed Blanc to the [[Pennsylvania courts of common pleas|court of common pleas]] to fill the remaining term of Gerald F. Flood, who had been elected to the [[Pennsylvania Superior Court]].{{sfn|Plain Speaker 1960}} Blanc won election to a full ten-year term on the court [[Philadelphia municipal election, 1961|in 1961]]. He developed [[Alzheimer's disease]] and was relieved of his duties on the court in 1964. Four years later, he died in [[Haverford State Hospital]] at the age of 71. He was buried in Mount Sinai Cemetery in Philadelphia.{{sfn|Inquirer 1968}}

